  "opinion": "As a retired man from Naples with a background in upper secondary education and a deep appreciation for community and tradition, I've watched how stereotypes can quietly undermine people's potential. Stereotype threat in STEM refers to the anxiety that arises when individuals fear their group's negative stereotypes about their abilities in science, technology, engineering, or math fields. For example, a young girl who grows up hearing that 'boys are better at math' might start doubting her own skills before even entering a classroom. This isn't just about individual confidence—it's a systemic issue that affects entire generations. In my time, I've seen how such threats can manifest in classrooms where students from marginalized backgrounds feel they don't belong, even when they're capable. Addressing this isn't just about policy changes; it's about fostering an environment where everyone feels valued and capable. I believe we should address stereotype threat through education that emphasizes inclusivity and celebrates diverse talents from the start. In Naples, where community and respect for elders are deeply rooted, we can model this by encouraging children to explore STEM without fear of judgment. By creating safe spaces for learning and highlighting role models from all backgrounds, we can help dismantle these harmful stereotypes. It's important to remember that every child deserves the chance to shine, regardless of their background or gender. My own experience with gardening and painting taught me that creativity and discipline go hand in hand—just as they do in STEM. We must nurture that same spirit of curiosity and resilience in every student.",
